* Interior/border splitting in c++ convolve was somewhat of a win. Is that also something we should add to median and connected components?\
Summary: Added and kept the border/interior split for native UInt8 C++ convolution. A further tap-precompute variant was tried and reverted because it was slower. I did not add the same structure to median or connected components: median is now routed through C++ std::nth_element for the native path, and connected components got better mileage from SAUF-specific changes: array-backed union-find, delayed compression, a small decision-tree scan, array-backed compact relabelling, UInt32 labels, and slab/window stitching.\
\
\
* Please check that the other ParallelCollect/Reduce do not use the Choose but Iter version\
Summary: Checked the relevant paths while refactoring convolution. The convolution stages no longer depend on Stage.choose for the retained window path; ChunkFunctions now handles chunk incRef/decRef around retained windows and uses map/collect-style stages. ParallelReduce already has the one-worker fast path and stays in list/window form. Chunk reference-counting was kept in StackProcessing/ChunkFunctions rather than pushed into SlimPipeline.\
\
\
* Could Median radius=1 in uint8 figure be the old code? Distance to c++-itk is a big compared to radius=3\
Summary: The UInt8 median policy was updated so radius 1 uses the native C++ nth_element slab kernel, while the intermediate UInt8 radii in the main plots use the Perreault-Hebert dense-histogram y-band implementation. The TeX captions now describe that split. The remaining gap to C++/ITK is therefore not just an old-code plot issue; it reflects IO, chunk/slab orchestration, output writing, and implementation differences around neighbourhood extraction and rank selection.\
\
\
* Please update tex with a description of the new Connected Component and c++ convolution.\
Summary: body.tex was updated with the benchmark-facing descriptions: StackProcessing connected components now uses the LMIP slab schedule for the main UInt8 memory plot, the median section notes the C++ nth_element policy, and the UInt8 benchmark discussion/captions describe the three-worker chunk pipeline. After the latest native UInt8 C++ convolution work, the figures were regenerated and copied into the TeX figure directory. A more detailed prose paragraph specifically naming the direct UInt8 native convolution kernel may still be worth adding if the report text should distinguish it from the earlier explicit UInt8-Float32-UInt8 route.\
\
\
* Please make int8, uint16/int16, int, float 32 with float32 kernels version of the c++-convolve \
Summary: Not completed. The native convolution work currently has direct UInt8 input/output with Float32 kernel and Float32 input/output with Float32 kernel. Benchmark fallback paths can still widen other integer types through Float32 and cast back, but there are not yet direct native C++ convolve entry points for Int8, UInt16, Int16, or Int32. Native median, separately, was added for UInt8, UInt16, Int32, and Float32.\
